<HEADLINE>
<P>
COUNTYWIDE FOCUS: OXNARD MAN TO OPPOSE GALLEGLY FOR GOP NOD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOANNA M. MILLER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 William Clifford Winter, an Oxnard resident and former Navy Seabee stationed 
at Port Hueneme, announced Friday he will challenge Rep. Elton Gallegly (R-Simi 
Valley) for the Republican nomination in a congressional district that 
stretches across the county. 
</P>
<P>
 Winter, 37, said his views calling for an open border between the United 
States and Mexico make him "more representative" of the people of Ventura 
County than Gallegly, who favors a more restrictive immigration policy. 
</P>
<P>
 "I think Congressman Gallegly is way out in left field on immigration," Winter 
said Friday. "He wants to change the Constitution and blockade the borders." 
</P>
<P>
 Winter also favors a proposal to allow commercial airlines to share the runway 
at the Naval Air Station at Point Mugu. And he said he will work to prevent the 
county's military bases from closing. 
</P>
<P>
 Gallegly said he recently met with Winter, who was far more supportive of the 
congressman's record. "He told me when he came to visit me that he supported 
everything I was doing and promised to support me after the primary." 
</P>
<P>
 But responding to his initial comments, Gallegly said, "Obviously we disagree 
on the immigration issue." 
</P>
<P>
 Winter's political experience includes an unsuccessful bid in 1992 for Oxnard 
City Council. Born in Jacksonville, Fla., Winter grew up in New Jersey, the son 
of a hardware store owner. He came to the Naval Construction Battalion Center 
at Port Hueneme in 1987 during his second four-year stint with the Navy. He 
received an honorable discharge in 1990. 
</P>
<P>
 Winter said he holds an associate's degree from the University of Maine and a 
bachelor of arts in communications from San Francisco State University. 
</P>
<P>
 Winter, who lists his profession as journalist and free-lance writer, said he 
worked briefly for the Navy in public relations after his discharge. Since 
then, he said, he worked as a nursing assistant in several locations and now 
works for a temporary employment agency in customer service for computers. 
JOANNA M. MILLER 
</P>
