<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEWSWIRE: SABO SPURNS METS, SIGNS DEAL WITH ORIOLES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Third baseman Chris Sabo, who became a free agent when the Cincinnati Reds 
made it clear they didn't want him back, agreed Friday to a $2-million, 
one-year contract with the Baltimore Orioles. 
</P>
<P>
 Sabo, a three-time All-Star who made $3.1 million last season, also had been 
negotiating with the New York Mets, who, according to his agent, offered more 
money. 
</P>
<P>
 Sabo, who will turn 32 on Wednesday, had 21 home runs and 82 runs batted in 
last season. 
</P>
<P>
 Also signing Friday was pitcher Greg Hibbard, formerly of the Chicago Cubs. He 
agreed to a $6.75-million, three-year deal with the Seattle Mariners. 
</P>
<P>
 Hibbard, a 29-year-old left-hander, was 15-11 in 1993. Tennis  
</P>
<P>
 Defending champion Pete Sampras reached the final of the New South Wales Open 
at Sydney, Australia, with a 6-3, 6-3 victory over Petr Korda of the Czech 
Republic in one semifinal. Ivan Lendl defeated American Todd Martin in the 
other, 6-4, 6-2. 
</P>
<P>
 In women's play, fifth-seeded Kimiko Date of Japan beat top-seeded Conchita 
Martinez of Spain, 6-3, 6-0, and will face American Patty Fendick in the 
semifinals. Fendick was a 6-3, 6-1 winner over Linda Ferrando of Italy. 
</P>
<P>
 Second-seeded Gabriela Sabatini of Argentina and third-seeded Mary Joe 
Fernandez will meet in the other women's semifinal. 
</P>
<P>
 Fernandez defeated sixth-seeded Zina Garrison-Jackson, 7-5, 6-2, and Sabatini 
beat Barbara Rittner of Germany, 6-1, 6-3. 
</P>
<P>
 Patrick McEnroe advanced to the semifinals of the New Zealand Open with a 
victory over Marcos Ondruska at Auckland, 2-6, 6-3, 6-4. Top-seeded Magnus 
Gustafsson of Sweden also advanced with a 6-1, 6-2 victory over Spain's Tomas 
Carbonell. Skiing  
</P>
<P>
 Katja Seizinger of Germany won a downhill World Cup event at Cortina 
D'Ampezzo, Italy, beating Austrian Veronika Stallmaier by 0.37 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
 The International Ski Federation ordered a rerun of last week's women's World 
Cup super-G at Altenmarkt, Austria, that was stopped because of bad conditions 
after 33 of 85 skiers had started. Miscellany  
</P>
<P>
 Nigel Mansell, who won the Formula One championship in 1992 and followed it up 
last season by becoming the first rookie to win the Indy car PPG Cup title, 
became the first driver to lap the Phoenix International Raceway one-mile oval 
in under 20 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
 He drove a new Lola-Ford around the track in a computer-timed 19.96 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
 Dodger catcher Mike Piazza and UCLA volleyball and basketball player Natalie 
Williams have been selected as the Amateur Athletic Foundation's Southern 
California male and female athletes of the year for 1993. Names in the News  
</P>
<P>
 UCLA reserve quarterback Rob Walker underwent arthroscopic surgery at UCLA 
Medical Center for torn cartilage in his left knee. He is expected to be ready 
for spring drills. . . . Sophomore wide receiver Tamarick Vanover says he wants 
to return to Florida State for his junior season, but athletic department 
officials won't clear him until questions about his financial assistance are 
resolved. . . . Lewis Sims, the North Carolina State basketball team's 
second-leading scorer, was ruled academically ineligible for the rest of the 
season. . . . Rolando Blackman of the New York Knicks was suspended for a game 
without pay and fined $2,000 for throwing a punch at David Wood of the Detroit 
Pistons. . . . Alex Crozier, coach of the Cal Poly women's soccer team, has 
been voted 1993 Division II coach of the year. 
</P>
