<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFLY: TELECOMMUNICATIONS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 AT&T Move Creates Fourth-Quarter Loss: New York-based AT&T said it will set 
aside $1.3 billion to comply with new accounting rules that chiefly cover how 
severance payments are reflected on a company's books.The move will reduce 
AT&T's fourth-quarter earnings after taxes by about 96 cents a share, resulting 
in a loss. Without it, the company said it would have earned $1.15 billion, or 
85 cents a share, which would be in line with analysts' expectations. In 
addition to the accounting charges, AT&T said its 1993 results will also 
reflect about $120 million in costs associated with restructuring NCR Corp., 
its computer manufacturing subsidiary. NCR last fall offered early retirement 
incentives to 5,000 of its 27,000 employees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
